00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:29.180
PROFESSOR: So what I would
like to discuss today

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:32.970
is just touch upon
what kind of problems

00:00:32.970 --> 00:00:37.460
the quantitative analysts
are solving in the commodity

00:00:37.460 --> 00:00:40.550
world, the problems
that are somewhat

00:00:40.550 --> 00:00:43.800
different from
the other markets.

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.590
And I'm sure you have the
whole year of lectures here

00:00:47.590 --> 00:00:50.420
from people in
different markets.

00:00:50.420 --> 00:00:55.160
And you will judge for yourself
that the models we're building

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:59.200
are somewhat, if not
completely, different.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:01.970
So this is my goal
today is just for you

00:01:01.970 --> 00:01:06.590
to have some taste of what kind
of models we're looking at.

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:12.330
So let's start.

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:37.350
Let's start with the following
abstract from the Dow Jones

00:01:37.350 --> 00:01:42.440
publication, the
dispatch which announced

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:49.730
in 2009 that the Trafigura--
which is the biggest

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:53.920
trader, one of the biggest
commodity and energy trader--

00:01:53.920 --> 00:01:56.720
is potentially on track to
post its best results ever

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:01.490
in fiscal 2009 on lower oil
prices and contango markets.

00:02:01.490 --> 00:02:07.650
Remember, 2008, just the year
before that, the oil prices

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:14.720
shot to the highest possible
level, to $159 per barrel.

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:17.680
And a lot of people
blamed the traders

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.730
for the high oil prices.

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:25.540
And yet, in 2008, when the
prices dropped-- in 2009,

00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:27.620
I'm sorry, next
year-- when the prices

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:31.590
dropped to $30 per barrel, as
you remember, to the lowest

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:37.100
possible level that
we remember, Trafigura

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:40.330
is about to make the
biggest profit ever.

00:02:40.330 --> 00:02:42.280
So it sounds like
a contradiction.

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:46.150
So they're making money on the
low oil prices and contango.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:50.850
And contango, which I have to
explain to you what it is-- I

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:58.520
assume that everybody here knows
what the futures contract is.

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:02.420
If not, just let me
know, and I will explain.

00:03:02.420 --> 00:03:09.440
It's very simple concept, so
don't be shy and just tell me.

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:13.320
So I would like to
show you how Trafigura

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:16.350
will make the record
profit in the year

00:03:16.350 --> 00:03:20.590
when the prices are at
the record low level,

00:03:20.590 --> 00:03:21.950
but they are in contango.

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:35.160
So this is the graph
of futures contracts,

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:41.040
futures prices, oil futures
prices on January 15, 2009.

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:43.330
Futures contract is
simply the contract

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:45.270
that allows you to
buy today-- let's

00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:49.390
say, in January--
the barrel of oil

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:51.050
for delivery in
some future time.

00:03:51.050 --> 00:03:52.720
That's all.

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:54.430
You always know
what the price will

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:58.570
be by looking into Wall Street
Journal, Section C. Open,

00:03:58.570 --> 00:03:59.640
you will see.

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:04.980
If you want to have
delivery in August,

00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:08.350
the price will be around, what?

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:10.040
$55?

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:16.200
If you want delivery on February
of next year-- so February,

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:19.510
2010-- the price will be $60.

00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:23.555
If you want delivery now,
the price will be $35.

00:04:23.555 --> 00:04:24.930
So if you want to
buy, basically,

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:29.180
the spot price--
for your knowledge,

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:31.510
there is no spot price, as such.

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:36.580
And whatever you see on
CNBC, for example, on TV,

00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:38.700
when they give you
the spot price of oil,

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:42.280
it's the price of the first
future contract-- so this one--

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.560
of the nearby, the most
nearby futures contract.

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:47.960
So as you can see,
this is the curve.

00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:53.130
And recall that the curve is
in contango if the prices are

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:54.940
monotone increasing.

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:57.160
If they are decreasing,
it's called backwardation.

00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:58.710
That's all.

00:04:58.710 --> 00:05:01.340
So just a useful
term for you to know.

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:04.940
So at that time, January
15th, the prices indeed

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:07.140
were monotone increasing.

00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:09.430
They're going from
$35 to February

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:11.450
and to $60 in February.

00:05:11.450 --> 00:05:12.780
So this is February of 2009.

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:15.110
This is February of 2010.

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:19.300
And we can see the prices
were going from $35 to $60.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:23.970
So let's now see how
Trafigura made money.

00:05:23.970 --> 00:05:25.980
Can you guess, by the way?

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:26.812
Yes.

00:05:26.812 --> 00:05:28.728
AUDIENCE: They borrowed
money, bought the spot

00:05:28.728 --> 00:05:30.579
and then sold the
futures contract?

00:05:30.579 --> 00:05:31.370
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:34.830
So that's precisely
what they've done.

00:05:34.830 --> 00:05:37.202
What is needed for that, though?

00:05:37.202 --> 00:05:39.474
There's one little
thing that's required.

00:05:39.474 --> 00:05:43.360
AUDIENCE: Low interest rates
and ability to buy the spot?

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:46.200
PROFESSOR: This price
is the ability to buy.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:49.591
But you need a little bit more.

00:05:49.591 --> 00:05:50.090
You need--

00:05:50.090 --> 00:05:50.980
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:52.317
PROFESSOR: I'm sorry?

00:05:52.317 --> 00:05:53.750
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:53.750 --> 00:05:55.170
PROFESSOR: No, no, you lock in.

00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:56.950
You bought at $35.

00:05:56.950 --> 00:05:58.220
AUDIENCE: Storage.

00:05:58.220 --> 00:05:59.970
PROFESSOR: Storage--
you need the storage.

00:05:59.970 --> 00:06:03.800
You need to be able to wait one
year, because you already sold

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:07.110
at $60 next year, in February.

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:10.040
So you locked in
a massive profit

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:14.450
of-- so this is your strategy.

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:16.640
Just borrow 35.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:17.480
Buy one barrel.

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:19.120
Store it.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:21.720
Then immediately sell,
so short means just go

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:25.710
and sell the one barrel
for next year at $60.

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:29.340
So you have-- you
made $25-- I'm sorry,

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:32.680
you made $25 just on commodity.

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:35.940
You have to-- on February,
you will get this-- February

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:38.140
next year you will get this $25.

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:41.600
You'll pay the interest, which
will be maybe, let's say 10%.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:45.590
So it will be $3.5.

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:48.410
So you made total profit $21.

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:53.120
If, like Trafigura, you have 50,
60 million barrels of storage,

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:55.590
you can easily
calculate how much money

00:06:55.590 --> 00:07:00.570
they have without any risk they
made in this particular year.

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:04.350
So whenever you hear that
traders are benefiting

00:07:04.350 --> 00:07:05.990
from the high prices, it's not.

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:09.370
Actually, if the same situations
existed in the high prices,

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:12.100
then the interest would
be substantially lower.

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:15.480
They could drop
their profit by 50%,

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:21.087
if, let's say, the same
where the prices $125

00:07:21.087 --> 00:07:23.231
to $135 to $160.

00:07:23.231 --> 00:07:23.730
Right?

00:07:23.730 --> 00:07:26.750
You would have the
enormous interest payment.

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:28.740
So in reality, you
need the low prices,

00:07:28.740 --> 00:07:30.636
but you would like
to have a contango.

00:07:30.636 --> 00:07:33.670
You really don't care,
price is low or high.

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:42.380
So to summarize,
we need to have--

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:46.840
I mean, just a little thing
here-- that the strategy works

00:07:46.840 --> 00:07:47.640
like a charm.

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:49.330
The only thing you
need is storage.

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:57.010
OK, let me now
invert the question.

00:07:57.010 --> 00:07:58.510
Let me ask you this
question-- let's

00:07:58.510 --> 00:08:01.690
say we have the same curve.

00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:07.870
We are on January
1st, 2009, and we

00:08:07.870 --> 00:08:12.680
are asked to get the storage.

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:16.650
You want to have your bosses
calling you and saying,

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:19.000
I mean, I need
storage, oil storage

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.940
from August to December.

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:28.450
So in August, we have the price
is, what, $55, in December $58.

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:32.260
You go and get me--
here's your credit card.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:34.990
Just go and get it.

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:39.600
Well, storage is usually--
you get it at the auctions.

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:43.740
So a lot of people come to
the auction, and they'll bid.

00:08:43.740 --> 00:08:47.370
So now you're going with the
boss's credit card, right?

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:50.310
And you have the
following dilemma--

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:56.280
if you borrow too little,
you will never get it.

00:08:56.280 --> 00:09:01.940
If you bid too much, you'll have
the winner's curse-- namely,

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:04.640
you will never be able
to recover the money

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:08.700
that you paid for that storage.

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:14.270
So you have to have-- before you
bid, you have to have a plan.

00:09:14.270 --> 00:09:18.580
How do you-- or strategy--
how do you recover the money

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:23.390
that you pay for the storage
through some foolproof,

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:28.560
riskless activity-- some
strategy like Trafigura.

00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:31.710
Remember, they have
the riskless strategy.

00:09:31.710 --> 00:09:33.240
They lock in the profit.

00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:36.970
They can go to sleep for
a year, and then vacation,

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:39.140
and then come back and
get this profit back.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:44.010
How do you-- in this
particular case, you have,

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:46.070
whenever you bid
something, you also

00:09:46.070 --> 00:09:48.270
have to have a plan
in mind how to recover

00:09:48.270 --> 00:09:52.090
this money and even more, to
get a little bit of profit.

00:09:52.090 --> 00:09:57.350
So my question to you-- you
need storage from August

00:09:57.350 --> 00:09:59.190
to December.

00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:00.240
How much would you bid?

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:07.310
These are the prices.

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:10.930
If you need more prices,
they're all here.

00:10:10.930 --> 00:10:12.930
So you need the storage
from August to December.

00:10:18.654 --> 00:10:21.195
AUDIENCE: Do the same thing?

00:10:21.195 --> 00:10:23.010
Do the same thing
they did before?

00:10:23.010 --> 00:10:25.218
PROFESSOR: So how much would
you bid for the storage?

00:10:25.218 --> 00:10:28.400
You don't have the storage, so
you have to-- when you get it,

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:33.050
then you do what we
did before, because

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:36.340
before what we did was assume
that we already have it.

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:41.670
Right now, you don't, but if
you win it, you will have it.

00:10:41.670 --> 00:10:43.670
But if you win it, you
have to have the strategy

00:10:43.670 --> 00:10:44.815
how to recover this money.

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:55.220
Yes?

00:10:55.220 --> 00:10:57.470
AUDIENCE: Depends on how
much profit you want to make.

00:10:57.470 --> 00:11:00.060
PROFESSOR: Well, it's
not, because remember,

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:03.081
you are competing
against other people.

00:11:03.081 --> 00:11:03.580
Right?

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:08.730
So if you become too greedy,
they will outbid you.

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:11.790
So let's say bid
one penny, right?

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:17.020
Assuming that you'll make--
so it should be-- what

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:19.940
is the highest you can bid?

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:21.335
AUDIENCE: $3?

00:11:21.335 --> 00:11:23.200
PROFESSOR: Uh-huh.

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:23.924
You say $3.

00:11:26.610 --> 00:11:31.544
All right, give me the
strategy that recovers that $3.

00:11:31.544 --> 00:11:35.030
AUDIENCE: But we do
the same process.

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:37.130
We borrow money, buy--

00:11:37.130 --> 00:11:38.630
PROFESSOR: You don't
have to borrow,

00:11:38.630 --> 00:11:39.880
because it's futures contract.

00:11:39.880 --> 00:11:45.940
You don't need-- you
just go long the August.

00:11:45.940 --> 00:11:48.740
So buy August, using
the futures contract,

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:51.160
and sell December using
the futures contract.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:52.770
You don't even need
to borrow money.

00:11:52.770 --> 00:11:57.250
You will need to borrow, maybe,
when you get to August, right?

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:01.280
Then when you have to pay $55,
then you'll borrow, right?

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:03.570
So you bid $3, you recovered $3.

00:12:03.570 --> 00:12:04.220
No profits.

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:07.690
So most likely, you
will bid $2.99, right?

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:09.200
That's the highest
probably, can go.

00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:12.601
You have to give yourself at
least a penny of a profit,

00:12:12.601 --> 00:12:13.100
right?

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:13.860
AUDIENCE: The interest.

00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:14.706
PROFESSOR: I'm sorry?

00:12:14.706 --> 00:12:15.872
AUDIENCE: Also the interest.

00:12:15.872 --> 00:12:18.320
PROFESSOR: Let's forget
about interest for a moment,

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:20.237
just for simplicity.

00:12:20.237 --> 00:12:22.570
In reality, of course, you
never should forget about it,

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:27.610
but in order not to make our
discussions too complicated,

00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:28.300
no interest.

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:35.030
So you're basically will be at
$2.99, it seems to me, right?

00:12:35.030 --> 00:12:38.130
You get a penny of profit,
and you have a strategy

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:39.227
if you get the storage.

00:12:39.227 --> 00:12:40.060
You know what to do.

00:12:40.060 --> 00:12:42.480
You immediately go buy August.

00:12:42.480 --> 00:12:45.430
Using futures contract, buy
August, and sell December,

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:48.170
locking in $3.

00:12:48.170 --> 00:12:51.670
Pay $2.99, if you manage
to win, if everybody is not

00:12:51.670 --> 00:12:54.140
as smart as you
are, and just bid--

00:12:54.140 --> 00:12:56.330
or maybe they want
bigger profit.

00:12:56.330 --> 00:12:57.570
You will win the storage.

00:12:57.570 --> 00:12:59.670
You will lock in.

00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:03.870
OK, and everybody agrees, right?

00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:07.010
This is actually a
standard strategy.

00:13:07.010 --> 00:13:09.280
People use it all the time.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:11.900
That's what I would
call-- that's what

00:13:11.900 --> 00:13:12.820
the trader would do.

00:13:12.820 --> 00:13:18.220
That's kind of the trader, so
a business guy would do that.

00:13:18.220 --> 00:13:21.520
This is a common strategy--
was very, very common,

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:22.540
let's say in the '90s.

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:27.910
What the quant will
do-- and that's

00:13:27.910 --> 00:13:31.290
where the added value of the
quant is to the organization--

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:34.030
they will do something
completely different.

00:13:34.030 --> 00:13:38.770
What they will do-- they
will, on January 1st,

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:42.430
they will sell something that
is called August-December spread

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:43.220
option.

00:13:43.220 --> 00:13:45.100
You heard the word
option, right?

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:50.390
Option is characterized by
the payout at expiration.

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:52.020
So we have expiration.

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:54.140
We have the payout.

00:13:54.140 --> 00:13:57.410
This is not your typical
options, not like IBM option.

00:13:57.410 --> 00:13:58.750
This is something different.

00:13:58.750 --> 00:14:04.730
The payout is determined at
the expiration, which is,

00:14:04.730 --> 00:14:08.261
let's say, July 31st, right
before the beginning of August,

00:14:08.261 --> 00:14:08.760
right?

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:13.130
You will look again at
the Wall Street Journal

00:14:13.130 --> 00:14:20.140
and look at the December and
August prices on July 31st.

00:14:20.140 --> 00:14:22.450
And if the difference
is positive--

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:25.700
this little plus sign means
that if it's positive--

00:14:25.700 --> 00:14:29.560
than you pay to the owner of
the option this difference.

00:14:29.560 --> 00:14:33.910
If it's negative, you pay zero.

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:37.710
You're more familiar with the
options where one of this thing

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:39.842
is just a fixed strike.

00:14:39.842 --> 00:14:41.050
It's called the fixed strike.

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:42.350
Here, there's no strike.

00:14:42.350 --> 00:14:46.860
It simply the difference between
December and August contract.

00:14:46.860 --> 00:14:49.527
But it's a
two-dimensional object,

00:14:49.527 --> 00:14:51.610
so it's a little bit more
complicated to value it.

00:14:51.610 --> 00:14:54.780
But there is a whole methodology
developed, the same way

00:14:54.780 --> 00:14:55.780
for the regular options.

00:14:55.780 --> 00:14:57.890
This is for the spread options.

00:14:57.890 --> 00:15:03.990
So the quant will sell this
spread option on August 1st.

00:15:03.990 --> 00:15:05.000
Why is it better?

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:11.670
Well, first of all, we have
