kind of cancel each other.

00:30:43.110 --> 00:30:45.270
So that's why this
sign is plus and minus.

00:30:45.270 --> 00:30:47.820
The same thing with others
options, and the same thing

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:49.300
with pure futures contract.

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:52.790
And that should be less
than the injection rate.

00:30:52.790 --> 00:30:55.900
The same thing with
withdrawal rate, right?

00:30:55.900 --> 00:31:02.160
I mean, it's a
similar consideration.

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:04.030
Now, maximum
capacity constraints,

00:31:04.030 --> 00:31:07.920
it tells me that if I start
with this inventory in my tank

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:11.380
at time 0, and this
is basically how much

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:14.770
I will get at any
time i, for any month

00:31:14.770 --> 00:31:20.540
i, that's how much I will have
in my tank by that time i.

00:31:20.540 --> 00:31:23.390
You have to believe me, because
it's not a trivial thing.

00:31:23.390 --> 00:31:25.590
But the same thing with
minimum constraints.

00:31:25.590 --> 00:31:27.630
What you really
have to understand,

00:31:27.630 --> 00:31:36.890
that unknowns are x, y,
z, v, and unfortunately,

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:39.540
omega is also unknown.

00:31:39.540 --> 00:31:43.220
Omega is just-- it's basically
these are the volumes.

00:31:43.220 --> 00:31:47.240
This is the kind of control
variable, the price.

00:31:47.240 --> 00:31:51.020
And the price can be-- the
spread can be positive,

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:53.620
can be negative, can be 0.

00:31:53.620 --> 00:31:58.610
And this is becoming a very
ugly, non-linear problem,

00:31:58.610 --> 00:31:59.610
very quickly.

00:31:59.610 --> 00:32:04.690
Very big, so you have
a lot of variables.

00:32:04.690 --> 00:32:16.180
For two years, you have, what,
12 times 11, which is 132.

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:19.310
Let me just-- no, 24.

00:32:19.310 --> 00:32:20.170
I'm sorry.

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:24.080
It's 24 times 23, so
it's 12 times-- so it's

00:32:24.080 --> 00:32:28.807
a big number of
variables, plus an equally

00:32:28.807 --> 00:32:31.390
big number of constraints, and
the constraints are non-linear.

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:38.280
So the problem is pretty hard.

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:47.730
I leave it up to you to
decide how to solve it.

00:32:47.730 --> 00:32:51.250
That's why they take
optimization courses here.

00:32:51.250 --> 00:32:56.150
I can suggest that there are
several approaches people

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:58.310
would take.

00:32:58.310 --> 00:33:01.100
There's approximation, where
this problem is approximated,

00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:03.940
let's say by linear programming,
or quadratic programming,

00:33:03.940 --> 00:33:06.170
or whatever you want.

00:33:06.170 --> 00:33:09.320
You can do it through
Monte-Carlo simulations.

00:33:09.320 --> 00:33:11.800
Or there is an
interesting approach

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:13.240
through the stochastic control.

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:18.050
I recommend you a paper
by Carmona and Ludkovski,

00:33:18.050 --> 00:33:23.485
exactly how to do this-- how
to make a decision of injecting

00:33:23.485 --> 00:33:27.830
oil or withdrawing oil based
on the stochastic control,

00:33:27.830 --> 00:33:31.450
stochastic optimization
methodology.

00:33:31.450 --> 00:33:37.750
But it is quite an
interesting paper.

00:33:37.750 --> 00:33:40.540
So either of these
approaches can be used.

00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:47.170
And they are used, and give you
sometimes different results,

00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:50.985
but you can look.

00:33:50.985 --> 00:33:51.860
Any questions so far?

00:33:57.632 --> 00:34:01.910
AUDIENCE: Is the
stochastic control solution

00:34:01.910 --> 00:34:05.830
an optimal solution
or exact solution?

00:34:10.240 --> 00:34:13.670
Is it giving the solution that
the Monte-Carlo simulation's

00:34:13.670 --> 00:34:14.650
approximating?

00:34:14.650 --> 00:34:17.739
PROFESSOR: Let me
put it this way.

00:34:17.739 --> 00:34:26.620
None of these solutions
is better, or prettier,

00:34:26.620 --> 00:34:29.500
or whatever, because
of the parameters

00:34:29.500 --> 00:34:31.230
that go into the problem.

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:35.440
And you can have the
most precise methodology,

00:34:35.440 --> 00:34:38.010
but if your parameters
are only 50%

00:34:38.010 --> 00:34:41.726
accurate-- in reality,
all those parameters

00:34:41.726 --> 00:34:43.350
necessarily for
Monte-Carlo simulations

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:44.899
with stochastic
control, we really

00:34:44.899 --> 00:34:45.940
don't know what they are.

00:34:45.940 --> 00:34:50.800
We can only can guess through
some implied market parameter

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:53.227
volatility, and so on.

00:34:53.227 --> 00:34:54.889
And if you're
wrong, you're wrong.

00:34:54.889 --> 00:34:59.250
Even your method can
be absolutely precise.

00:34:59.250 --> 00:35:03.340
I like it, because it's really
very nice mathematics there.

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:09.100
We personally don't do that.

00:35:09.100 --> 00:35:11.560
I'm not going to tell
you what we're using,

00:35:11.560 --> 00:35:14.260
but we do something different.

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:19.090
And our methodology is
chosen to be robust.

00:35:19.090 --> 00:35:21.930
We chose it because we
want the methodology

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:23.750
to be extremely robust.

00:35:23.750 --> 00:35:26.797
So we don't want
small changes-- we

00:35:26.797 --> 00:35:28.380
don't want to have
the situation where

00:35:28.380 --> 00:35:32.210
small changes, which usually
comes when you overparametrize.

00:35:32.210 --> 00:35:35.980
I mean, people like to go and
later-- in the second half--

00:35:35.980 --> 00:35:38.430
I will discuss some of
the models people use.

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:41.970
For example, they
see the richness

00:35:41.970 --> 00:35:44.520
of the behavior of
the prices, and they

00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:46.140
want to introduce
a lot of parameters

00:35:46.140 --> 00:35:47.570
to capture this richness.

00:35:47.570 --> 00:35:50.270
By that, they sacrifice the
stability and robustness.

00:35:50.270 --> 00:35:53.380
So little changes in the
parameters and the value

00:35:53.380 --> 00:35:55.060
can change substantially.

00:35:55.060 --> 00:35:57.330
So we prefer a
different approach,

00:35:57.330 --> 00:36:00.880
where we maybe a sacrifice
some of the value,

00:36:00.880 --> 00:36:04.500
but we will gain the
robustness, stability.

00:36:04.500 --> 00:36:07.750
And this is the most
important thing.

00:36:07.750 --> 00:36:10.800
And most importantly, everything
that we use in the model

00:36:10.800 --> 00:36:14.850
can be verified by the outside
regulators and controllers,

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:18.550
which in this day and age
is extremely important.

00:36:18.550 --> 00:36:20.770
Because these days,
to have a model that

00:36:20.770 --> 00:36:23.990
is calibrated-- even
the word calibrated

00:36:23.990 --> 00:36:29.360
causes a lot of
antennas just going up.

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:30.860
So we try not to
calibrate anything.

00:36:30.860 --> 00:36:33.370
Everything that we
do can be verified--

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.269
every little brick that
goes into the model

00:36:35.269 --> 00:36:37.310
can be traded in the
market, and can be verified.

00:36:40.650 --> 00:36:45.010
This is very, very important
in this day and age.

00:36:45.010 --> 00:36:45.678
Yes?

00:36:45.678 --> 00:36:46.594
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:46.594 --> 00:36:49.660
What do you mean by
calibration [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:49.660 --> 00:36:52.940
PROFESSOR: We'll get to
that, but very quick answer

00:36:52.940 --> 00:36:57.300
is this-- just you have a lot
of parameters in the model.

00:36:57.300 --> 00:36:59.640
I'll show some of the
models people use.

00:36:59.640 --> 00:37:02.560
These parameters are not-- you
don't see them in the market.

00:37:02.560 --> 00:37:05.080
It's the result of your model.

00:37:05.080 --> 00:37:09.460
It's because you chose
this particular model.

00:37:09.460 --> 00:37:11.700
Black-Scholes uses
one parameter.

00:37:11.700 --> 00:37:14.850
If you use Black-Scholes
with jump-diffusion term,

00:37:14.850 --> 00:37:17.770
and some other, you introduce
another ten parameters.

00:37:17.770 --> 00:37:21.370
These parameters
are not observable,

00:37:21.370 --> 00:37:25.257
so you have to somehow calibrate
it to some market data.

00:37:25.257 --> 00:37:27.340
And the calibration becoming
a pretty interesting,

00:37:27.340 --> 00:37:30.040
because calibration usually is
done through some kind of least

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:31.000
squares approach.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.250
So you try to look at
the observable data,

00:37:35.250 --> 00:37:39.030
and then adjust your parameters
using some least squares

00:37:39.030 --> 00:37:42.000
approach to match that data.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:46.100
Least squares is
notoriously bad-- problem,

00:37:46.100 --> 00:37:48.010
so you may have many solutions.

00:37:48.010 --> 00:37:49.930
The solution set
can be very flat,

00:37:49.930 --> 00:37:51.470
so you can stop very early.

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:54.290
So there are problems
with least squares.

00:37:54.290 --> 00:37:58.780
It's non-linear optimization, so
by itself, it's very difficult.

00:37:58.780 --> 00:38:00.760
So calibration can be
very, very unstable.

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:05.641
Any more?

00:38:05.641 --> 00:38:06.140
OK.

00:38:13.590 --> 00:38:15.280
Now I have to tell
you the secret--

00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:16.740
there is no Santa Claus.

00:38:16.740 --> 00:38:23.680
Just remember, I was telling you
that I go and I sold the option

00:38:23.680 --> 00:38:26.670
to get 447.

00:38:26.670 --> 00:38:27.616
I've got the option.

00:38:27.616 --> 00:38:30.760
In reality there is
no option market.

00:38:30.760 --> 00:38:32.401
Nobody will buy this
option from you.

00:38:32.401 --> 00:38:34.150
The market for this
option-- non-existent.

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:43.130
Now what do we do in this
particular situation?

00:38:43.130 --> 00:38:49.260
That's where the whole beauty of
Black-Scholes comes into play.

00:38:49.260 --> 00:38:51.990
Black-Scholes didn't
get the Nobel Prize

00:38:51.990 --> 00:38:56.290
for integrating some very
simple payoff function that you

00:38:56.290 --> 00:39:00.045
can do in first year of school.

00:39:00.045 --> 00:39:05.470
They got the Nobel Prize-- or
they got kind of appreciation

00:39:05.470 --> 00:39:07.220
for what they've done,
because they showed

00:39:07.220 --> 00:39:11.710
that, with this value, they also
have the strategy that allows

00:39:11.710 --> 00:39:14.630
you by doing something every
day or every half a day,

00:39:14.630 --> 00:39:15.880
you can replicate this value.

00:39:15.880 --> 00:39:20.770
So if you paid for
the option $5, then

00:39:20.770 --> 00:39:25.430
you can show what
to do every day.

00:39:25.430 --> 00:39:27.660
They tell you what to
do every day in order

00:39:27.660 --> 00:39:30.690
to get back this $5 at the end.

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:33.850
So that's what their
main achievement.

00:39:33.850 --> 00:39:38.560
Or if I sold an option,
and received $5,

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:42.910
then I will do
something that-- I

00:39:42.910 --> 00:39:47.620
will use this $5 to replicate
any payout I owe at the end.

00:39:47.620 --> 00:39:49.680
So I sold it to
you, for example.

00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:52.300
So at the end, I owe you $50.

00:39:52.300 --> 00:39:56.000
But they showed how,
through the dynamic hedging,

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:59.540
and using this $5 that
I receive up front,

00:39:59.540 --> 00:40:02.250
I can be able to meet
my obligations to you.

00:40:02.250 --> 00:40:04.770
So they showed how to replicate
the payout of the option.

00:40:07.720 --> 00:40:12.310
So in reality, I don't
have to have the market.

00:40:12.310 --> 00:40:15.020
If I sold somebody
an option for 47,

00:40:15.020 --> 00:40:16.790
I don't have to have
anybody who buys it.

00:40:16.790 --> 00:40:19.800
What I will do, I will simply
use this dynamic hedging

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:22.410
strategy that
Black-Scholes advised me,

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:25.680
adopt it to the spread
options, which at the end

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:30.710
will produce for me 447.

00:40:30.710 --> 00:40:32.450
That's it.

00:40:32.450 --> 00:40:35.440
But here again,
this is another task

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:37.170
that quants will have to do.

00:40:37.170 --> 00:40:39.020
Not only they will
find the value.

00:40:39.020 --> 00:40:42.690
They will produce every
day the strategy that

00:40:42.690 --> 00:40:46.510
allows you to extract this 447.

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:49.070
So we already showed what
to do with the storage.

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:53.610
But now you have to do on
the next level of complexity.

00:40:53.610 --> 00:40:57.420
You have to tell to the trader
what to do every day in order

00:40:57.420 --> 00:41:01.340
to, in reality, get this 447
from selling this option.

00:41:01.340 --> 00:41:05.505
So you told this trader,
I'm selling this portfolio

00:41:05.505 --> 00:41:09.550
for $100,000 for the storage.

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:12.500
OK, so, but there's
nobody to sell it.

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:13.910
And you'll say, don't worry.

00:41:13.910 --> 00:41:16.320
I will do it through
dynamic hedging.

00:41:16.320 --> 00:41:19.520
At the end, you will
get your $100,000.

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:21.210
So he will believe you.

00:41:21.210 --> 00:41:22.220
And then he will do it.

00:41:22.220 --> 00:41:23.300
He will get $100,000.

00:41:23.300 --> 00:41:25.850
Then, on the next level you
have to work with the guy who

00:41:25.850 --> 00:41:27.260
operates the storage.

00:41:27.260 --> 00:41:30.220
And you will tell the
person when to inject oil,

00:41:30.220 --> 00:41:33.542
and when to withdraw, and to
get all of this magic which

00:41:33.542 --> 00:41:34.500
we've discussed before.

00:41:38.630 --> 00:41:46.470
So I think it'll be
a very logical point

00:41:46.470 --> 00:41:47.980
for me right now to stop.

00:41:47.980 --> 00:41:50.710
And in the next
half, we'll discuss

00:41:50.710 --> 00:41:53.620
how to model the power plant.

00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:56.730
So we're going to
the next topic.

00:42:02.080 --> 00:42:06.850
So far, we have
covered how to model

00:42:06.850 --> 00:42:11.300
a physical asset named storage.

00:42:11.300 --> 00:42:17.970
The same approach can be used
to model practically everything

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:19.240
that we're interested in.

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:22.630
For example, we can
use the same thing

00:42:22.630 --> 00:42:27.440
to model the tankers,
power plants, these storage

00:42:27.440 --> 00:42:31.670
refineries, anything,
power lines, pipelines,

00:42:31.670 --> 00:42:36.890
everything can be modeled
using this methodology.

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:41.670
Of course, the nature of
the beast will be different.

00:42:41.670 --> 00:42:45.150
And you have to understand the
nuances and the-- as I said,

00:42:45.150 --> 00:42:48.050
the constraints.

00:42:48.050 --> 00:42:50.380
This modeling--
for example, tanker

00:42:50.380 --> 00:42:53.440
requires understanding
of all the routes,

00:42:53.440 --> 00:42:59.780
and the constraints in the
ports, and all these things.

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:03.350
But the conceptual philosophical
approach is the same.

00:43:03.350 --> 00:43:04.950
You have to find
some optionality

00:43:04.950 --> 00:43:07.530
and that's some
additional value.

00:43:07.530 --> 00:43:12.530
So I obviously don't have time
to go over the whole thing.

00:43:12.530 --> 00:43:16.770
But let's, again, for you
to have a taste of this,

00:43:16.770 --> 00:43:20.546
let me just-- let's decide
how to model the power plant.

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:27.600
Assume that you are the manager
of the merchant power plant.

00:43:27.600 --> 00:43:31.780
Merchant means that you decide
when to run it, or not run it.

00:43:31.780 --> 00:43:36.661
You run it to maximize the
profit of this power plant.

00:43:40.220 --> 00:43:42.410
So how do you decide?

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:45.310
Let's say you decide once
a day, in the morning,

00:43:45.310 --> 00:43:49.920
whether to turn it on or turn
it off, or not to turn it on.

00:43:49.920 --> 00:43:52.580
So how do you decide?

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:55.090
Well, sounds complicated.

00:43:55.090 --> 00:43:56.794
In reality, it's very simple.

00:43:56.794 --> 00:44:00.660
You wake up in the morning.

00:44:00.660 --> 00:44:03.790
You look, first of
all, at the newspaper

00:44:03.790 --> 00:44:07.550
and find out what's the
price of electricity today.

00:44:07.550 --> 00:44:09.690
And price of electricity
you know for each hour--

00:44:09.690 --> 00:44:12.070
sometimes for each 15 minutes.

00:44:12.070 --> 00:44:13.430
It's determined.

00:44:13.430 --> 00:44:16.620
So you know for each hour,
or maybe the daily price,

00:44:16.620 --> 00:44:19.930
enough for the whole day.

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:21.260
So that's the price.

00:44:21.260 --> 00:44:25.240
If you sell it, that's how
much money you will get.

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:28.220
On the other hand, to produce
one megawatt-hour of power,

00:44:28.220 --> 00:44:30.080
you have to do something.

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:32.910
You have to turn
on your turbines.

00:44:32.910 --> 00:44:34.795
So you have to bring some fuel.

00:44:34.795 --> 00:44:40.300
You have to put some fuel into
the turbines, just to make them

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:45.210
move, and produce electricity.

00:44:45.210 --> 00:44:46.120
Fuel can be anything.

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:50.770
Let's say it's natural
gas, but some fuel.

00:44:50.770 --> 00:44:53.850
Now you have to
determine-- so you

00:44:53.850 --> 00:44:58.120
know how much money you'll get
for one megawatt-hour of power,

00:44:58.120 --> 00:44:59.850
right?

00:44:59.850 --> 00:45:03.270
But how much it will
cost you to produce it?

00:45:03.270 --> 00:45:05.730
So how much fuel you
need to determine

00:45:05.730 --> 00:45:07.680
how much-- first of all,
how much it costs you

00:45:07.680 --> 00:45:10.940
in terms of fuel to produce
this one megawatt-hour,

00:45:10.940 --> 00:45:13.650
you have to know the
efficiency of the plant.

00:45:13.650 --> 00:45:17.090
Because efficiency of
the plant is telling you

00:45:17.090 --> 00:45:24.270
how much units of fuel--
let's say how much MmBTUs,

00:45:24.270 --> 00:45:27.610
so millions British thermal
units of natural gas, that's

00:45:27.610 --> 00:45:33.150
how it's measured-- how
much MmBTUs of natural gas

00:45:33.150 --> 00:45:36.590
you have to burn to
produce one megawatt-hour.

00:45:36.590 --> 00:45:41.570
Well, this measure of
efficiency for the power plant

00:45:41.570 --> 00:45:43.440
is something called heat rate.

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:46.830
So heat rate is exactly
this coefficient

00:45:46.830 --> 00:45:54.485
by which you multiply the-- so
if I say that heat rate is 7,

00:45:54.485 --> 00:46:00.760
it means that I need 7
MmBTUs of natural gas

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:05.720
to produce one megawatt-hour
of power-- that's all.

00:46:05.720 --> 00:46:09.790
So in our case, there's
nothing to be concerned about.

00:46:09.790 --> 00:46:15.190
It's just simply some
constant that is given.

00:46:15.190 --> 00:46:19.640
It's some constant
between 7 to 20.

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:23.130
20 is a very inefficient
plant, very rarely run.

00:46:23.130 --> 00:46:26.690
Seven is right now more
kind of a standard constant.

00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:30.340
That's the constant
corresponding

00:46:30.340 --> 00:46:32.790
to the natural gas
power plant, which

