00:50:13.660 --> 00:50:15.660
That's what, again,
quants will do

00:50:15.660 --> 00:50:18.540
using already the experience
from other markets, and so on.

00:50:18.540 --> 00:50:21.200
You already heard
the other lectures.

00:50:21.200 --> 00:50:25.500
So what we'll do, we'll first
look at the distribution

00:50:25.500 --> 00:50:27.400
of power prices to see.

00:50:27.400 --> 00:50:30.060
Because I don't
know how to model

00:50:30.060 --> 00:50:32.590
the evolution of power prices.

00:50:32.590 --> 00:50:35.150
I know if I use simply
Brownian motion-- let's

00:50:35.150 --> 00:50:36.610
say it's my first idea.

00:50:36.610 --> 00:50:39.180
Well, let's see.

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:42.560
Brownian motion gives
us the distribution

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:45.810
which is, as you remember,
at any point of time is

00:50:45.810 --> 00:50:48.160
kind of normally distributed.

00:50:48.160 --> 00:50:52.940
If I look at the terminal
distribution of price, which

00:50:52.940 --> 00:50:56.810
is driven by Brownian motion--
if I assume that the price is

00:50:56.810 --> 00:50:58.800
driven by Brownian
motion, then at the end,

00:50:58.800 --> 00:51:01.360
I'll get the normal
distribution.

00:51:01.360 --> 00:51:04.900
So if I look at the, say
equity-- this is S&amp;P 500--

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:09.210
indeed it's-- we all know
that S&amp;P has fat tails, right?

00:51:09.210 --> 00:51:13.690
But as we can see in a moment,
this is not a fat tail.

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:16.840
This is very close to
the normal distribution.

00:51:16.840 --> 00:51:18.950
For the equity guys,
of course, for the guys

00:51:18.950 --> 00:51:22.830
who trade the stocks, it's
an enormously fat tail.

00:51:22.830 --> 00:51:25.260
But from the commodity
point of view,

00:51:25.260 --> 00:51:28.090
this is just perfect,
normal distribution.

00:51:28.090 --> 00:51:31.850
This is the distribution
that we deal with.

00:51:31.850 --> 00:51:36.920
This is-- the tails
here are just-- so

00:51:36.920 --> 00:51:40.790
the normal distribution just
out of the window immediately.

00:51:40.790 --> 00:51:42.470
So Brownian motion
out of the window--

00:51:42.470 --> 00:51:45.260
we cannot construct this
distribution of the terminal

00:51:45.260 --> 00:51:50.280
prices of power using that.

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:51.060
That's one thing.

00:51:51.060 --> 00:51:54.080
So we have very fat tails.

00:51:54.080 --> 00:51:55.960
And this is the kind
of the parameters

00:51:55.960 --> 00:51:58.110
that specify the distribution.

00:51:58.110 --> 00:52:01.450
If I look at the, let's
say the equity index,

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:03.790
the kurtosis is very
close to the kurtosis

00:52:03.790 --> 00:52:10.380
of the normal distribution,
which is 3 exactly.

00:52:10.380 --> 00:52:11.930
But if I look at
the Nord Pool, which

00:52:11.930 --> 00:52:15.970
is the power prices in
Scandinavian countries,

00:52:15.970 --> 00:52:17.200
kurtosis is 26.

00:52:17.200 --> 00:52:19.940
If I look at the
one-hour price, it's 76.

00:52:19.940 --> 00:52:27.130
So it is, as you can see, as
far from normal as possible.

00:52:27.130 --> 00:52:28.505
And we've seen it
in the picture.

00:52:28.505 --> 00:52:31.230
And these are the numbers
corresponding to that.

00:52:31.230 --> 00:52:35.730
Moreover, look at the
behavior of the prices.

00:52:35.730 --> 00:52:39.750
This is the price in Texas, for
example, power prices in Texas.

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:42.890
What immediately jumps-- I
mean, look at the prices,

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:45.660
and say, wow, how is
it different from what

00:52:45.660 --> 00:52:49.200
you see, let's say, in the
equity world, the stock market,

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:50.270
for example?

00:52:50.270 --> 00:52:53.220
What is it that
immediately jumps at you?

00:52:56.330 --> 00:52:57.661
What is different here?

00:53:01.430 --> 00:53:02.260
Go ahead.

00:53:02.260 --> 00:53:03.703
There's no right
or wrong answer.

00:53:03.703 --> 00:53:04.430
AUDIENCE: Spikes.

00:53:04.430 --> 00:53:07.460
PROFESSOR: Spikes--
that's the key word.

00:53:07.460 --> 00:53:10.570
Like no other market,
we have spikes here.

00:53:10.570 --> 00:53:14.460
That's a major,
major issue for us

00:53:14.460 --> 00:53:16.660
from the modeling point of view.

00:53:16.660 --> 00:53:18.530
You take any standard,
say Brownian motion,

00:53:18.530 --> 00:53:20.580
it will never
exhibit the spikes.

00:53:20.580 --> 00:53:22.310
Not only that, the
volatility, of course,

00:53:22.310 --> 00:53:26.090
of the prices, as we
already expect, is huge.

00:53:26.090 --> 00:53:27.710
It's hundreds.

00:53:27.710 --> 00:53:30.290
S&amp;P volatility right
now is 10% percent.

00:53:30.290 --> 00:53:35.460
This is 100, 200,
sometimes 1,000, right?

00:53:35.460 --> 00:53:38.340
All the intuition you
have about the behavior

00:53:38.340 --> 00:53:43.370
of the prices, the behavior
of the random variables,

00:53:43.370 --> 00:53:47.570
is mostly evolved,
all this intuition,

00:53:47.570 --> 00:53:51.000
under this 10, 15, 20%
volatility assumption.

00:53:54.140 --> 00:53:56.990
When the variables behave in
a completely different way

00:53:56.990 --> 00:54:03.510
when they have volatility
of 100% or 200% or 300%,

00:54:03.510 --> 00:54:08.890
so that's another thing that
will be challenging us, spikes

00:54:08.890 --> 00:54:11.080
and high volatility.

00:54:11.080 --> 00:54:12.710
It's just the same thing.

00:54:12.710 --> 00:54:14.470
It's everywhere,
so I just wanted

00:54:14.470 --> 00:54:16.750
to bring-- a different
region of the country,

00:54:16.750 --> 00:54:18.640
it will be exactly
the same thing.

00:54:18.640 --> 00:54:22.010
So it's common thing.

00:54:22.010 --> 00:54:24.900
So if you look, and start
to summarize what we're

00:54:24.900 --> 00:54:28.090
trying to capture
is-- mean reversion

00:54:28.090 --> 00:54:30.350
and spikes are more or
less the same thing,

00:54:30.350 --> 00:54:34.890
so we know if we go far
away, it will go back--

00:54:34.890 --> 00:54:37.390
high kurtosis,
regime switching, I

00:54:37.390 --> 00:54:42.510
will talk about that in a
moment-- and non-stationarity.

00:54:42.510 --> 00:54:45.930
That goes without saying.

00:54:45.930 --> 00:54:50.380
That's true for
most of the markets.

00:54:50.380 --> 00:54:52.360
And now the problem that
we have to capture--

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:55.250
or not the problem
but another phenomenon

00:54:55.250 --> 00:54:59.880
that we have to capture--
that the power and the fuel,

00:54:59.880 --> 00:55:04.870
natural gas, exhibit a
very particular structure

00:55:04.870 --> 00:55:05.750
of the correlation.

00:55:05.750 --> 00:55:07.560
So correlation is not a number.

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:10.540
It's dependent the heat
rate in the market.

00:55:10.540 --> 00:55:13.239
Remember heat rate is the
efficiency of the power plant

00:55:13.239 --> 00:55:14.530
that are running in the market.

00:55:14.530 --> 00:55:18.120
Depending on the efficiency, you
may have very high correlation

00:55:18.120 --> 00:55:19.330
or low correlation.

00:55:19.330 --> 00:55:21.460
We'll discuss that at the
end of this talk, which

00:55:21.460 --> 00:55:23.370
is why this here.

00:55:23.370 --> 00:55:25.800
Right now, I'm giving you
something that we observe,

00:55:25.800 --> 00:55:31.040
and our models, preferably,
should capture that as well.

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:35.990
So requirements for our
model are pretty intense,

00:55:35.990 --> 00:55:40.880
and pretty difficult. I
don't think that you ever

00:55:40.880 --> 00:55:43.390
assume the requirement
of the correlation

00:55:43.390 --> 00:55:46.240
should have some particular
structure, just depending

00:55:46.240 --> 00:55:47.590
on some parameters, and so on.

00:55:54.320 --> 00:55:56.815
OK, any questions?

00:56:01.490 --> 00:56:04.840
So the models typically--
the first thing people do,

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:08.370
they take the models that they
know, and they try to apply.

00:56:08.370 --> 00:56:10.834
Let's just very quickly
go through the models.

00:56:10.834 --> 00:56:12.500
I mean, you've seen
these models already

00:56:12.500 --> 00:56:14.520
in the previous lectures, right?

00:56:14.520 --> 00:56:16.900
Let's start with the
straightforward geometric

00:56:16.900 --> 00:56:20.830
Brownian motion, which out of
the window right away, right?

00:56:20.830 --> 00:56:25.810
I mean you agree, because
no spikes, no high--

00:56:25.810 --> 00:56:28.620
no correlation
structure, nothing.

00:56:28.620 --> 00:56:34.111
So it's clear that in order
to-- we want to kind of start

00:56:34.111 --> 00:56:36.110
with Brownian motion,
geometric Brownian motion,

00:56:36.110 --> 00:56:40.340
try to maybe modify
it a little bit.

00:56:40.340 --> 00:56:42.060
So what is spike?

00:56:42.060 --> 00:56:43.972
Spike means that
just things go up,

00:56:43.972 --> 00:56:45.180
and then they're pulled back.

00:56:45.180 --> 00:56:47.290
So there should be some
mean reversion, right?

00:56:47.290 --> 00:56:50.204
So mean reversion
is good, right?

00:56:50.204 --> 00:56:51.620
But unfortunately,
mean reversion,

00:56:51.620 --> 00:56:56.490
if you-- first of all, it's
pretty strong, so it goes,

00:56:56.490 --> 00:56:59.330
remember, if the price
goes from $30 to $1,000,

00:56:59.330 --> 00:57:03.840
and go back to $30,
mean reversion should

00:57:03.840 --> 00:57:05.670
be extremely strong, right?

00:57:05.670 --> 00:57:08.870
Second of all, what pushes
it to the $1,000 level?

00:57:08.870 --> 00:57:13.450
You need to have a jump.

00:57:13.450 --> 00:57:16.910
So that's why people
introduce the jumps.

00:57:16.910 --> 00:57:21.100
So we have mean
reversion, jumps; jumps

00:57:21.100 --> 00:57:23.250
and mean reversion.

00:57:23.250 --> 00:57:30.430
Still it is becoming
pretty clear

00:57:30.430 --> 00:57:32.970
that this will not work
for the following reason:

00:57:32.970 --> 00:57:35.590
it goes from $30
to $1,000, and then

00:57:35.590 --> 00:57:37.380
it goes back,
because it's a spike.

00:57:37.380 --> 00:57:39.760
It goes back within
three or four days.

00:57:39.760 --> 00:57:40.505
It comes back.

00:57:43.170 --> 00:57:45.620
So the mean reversion
should be extremely strong.

00:57:45.620 --> 00:57:48.100
The force of pulling back
should be extremely strong.

00:57:48.100 --> 00:57:52.500
But if it's so strong
that it moves you back

00:57:52.500 --> 00:57:56.200
from $1,000 to $30,
imagine what it does when

00:57:56.200 --> 00:57:57.980
you're on the level of $30.

00:57:57.980 --> 00:58:01.120
Because it will be completely
flat-- just nothing,

00:58:01.120 --> 00:58:02.490
you could not move there, right?

00:58:02.490 --> 00:58:06.860
So people observed that,
and introduced, well, they

00:58:06.860 --> 00:58:08.360
figured out maybe
the mean reversion

00:58:08.360 --> 00:58:10.470
will be different at
the level of $1,000

00:58:10.470 --> 00:58:13.450
than when you are at
the normal level of $30,

00:58:13.450 --> 00:58:14.740
so the difference.

00:58:14.740 --> 00:58:17.600
So you introduce right now
so-called regime switching.

00:58:17.600 --> 00:58:19.410
So it means that
all the parameters

00:58:19.410 --> 00:58:22.510
change, so you introduce
the kind of the high price

00:58:22.510 --> 00:58:25.060
level, low price level,
parameters change.

00:58:25.060 --> 00:58:29.220
And now we're getting
to the example

00:58:29.220 --> 00:58:32.410
that we discussed
in the first half.

00:58:32.410 --> 00:58:35.560
You end up with the
model with 10 parameters,

00:58:35.560 --> 00:58:38.890
12 parameters, which is
absolutely impossible

00:58:38.890 --> 00:58:41.010
to manage.

00:58:41.010 --> 00:58:44.630
I mean, I can give
you another, probably,

00:58:44.630 --> 00:58:48.220
hour discussing why
this approach in general

00:58:48.220 --> 00:58:50.480
is not good.

00:58:50.480 --> 00:58:53.290
And not just in commodities,
but everywhere else.

00:58:53.290 --> 00:58:56.270
I mean, I'm not a big fan of
making the models extremely

00:58:56.270 --> 00:59:01.410
complicated, because
introduction of one complexity

00:59:01.410 --> 00:59:03.827
leads to introduction
of another complexity.

00:59:03.827 --> 00:59:05.410
And you just cannot
manage this thing.

00:59:05.410 --> 00:59:06.990
It's impossible to manage.

00:59:06.990 --> 00:59:10.820
Theoretically, it looks
fantastic-- unmanageable.

00:59:10.820 --> 00:59:15.070
So we have to figure
out something else.

00:59:15.070 --> 00:59:17.080
So all these
methodologies-- and I

00:59:17.080 --> 00:59:19.590
put them there-- the
methodologies people actually

00:59:19.590 --> 00:59:25.230
use, the stochastic volatility,
the regime switching,

00:59:25.230 --> 00:59:28.150
multiple jumps, and so on.

00:59:28.150 --> 00:59:35.080
This-- it's all used, but it's
not what I want to suggest.

00:59:35.080 --> 00:59:37.650
I want to suggest something
completely different.

00:59:37.650 --> 00:59:39.620
These are the methodologies
that typically

00:59:39.620 --> 00:59:43.845
are coming from fixed-income
world or foreign exchange

00:59:43.845 --> 00:59:45.040
or equities and so on.

00:59:45.040 --> 00:59:49.050
I want to introduce something
completely different.

00:59:49.050 --> 00:59:52.180
Any questions so far?

00:59:52.180 --> 00:59:54.970
So I want to introduce
the methodology which

00:59:54.970 --> 00:59:58.070
is more suitable and
more understandable from

00:59:58.070 --> 00:59:59.580
the commodity point of view.

00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:02.110
Because actually, what's
the price of commodity?

01:00:02.110 --> 01:00:06.380
Price of commodity is
driven by only two things.

01:00:06.380 --> 01:00:08.394
Can you guess which?

01:00:08.394 --> 01:00:09.560
AUDIENCE: Supply and demand.

01:00:09.560 --> 01:00:13.080
PROFESSOR: Exactly, supply
and demand-- that's all it is.

01:00:13.080 --> 01:00:14.400
That's what we'll try to do.

01:00:14.400 --> 01:00:19.100
Maybe we can-- we have a hard
time modeling the commodity

01:00:19.100 --> 01:00:22.190
prices using just these
standard methodologies

01:00:22.190 --> 01:00:27.430
from different markets,
which rely only on the prices

01:00:27.430 --> 01:00:28.760
themselves.

01:00:28.760 --> 01:00:32.900
Maybe if I introduce some
fundamental modeling as well,

01:00:32.900 --> 01:00:36.820
I can do it without losing
the most important part

01:00:36.820 --> 01:00:39.930
of this model, is it
matches the market data.

01:00:39.930 --> 01:00:44.460
So I have to-- A: I want
to model supply and demand.

01:00:44.460 --> 01:00:50.210
But I also would like to match
every market data that I have.

01:00:50.210 --> 01:00:52.750
So maybe I introduce
a completely different

01:00:52.750 --> 01:00:54.890
complexity, maybe not.

01:00:54.890 --> 01:01:01.710
So let's try to see if I
can succeed here or not.

01:01:01.710 --> 01:01:04.800
Before we're going to go
into the depths of this,

01:01:04.800 --> 01:01:07.466
let's discuss how the
power prices are formed.

01:01:19.130 --> 01:01:22.550
Power prices are formed
in the following way--

01:01:22.550 --> 01:01:29.520
let's say that the market
consists of two power plants.

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:32.930
And there's Generator
One and Generator Two.

01:01:32.930 --> 01:01:40.830
Every day, they get prices of
power formed at the auction.

01:01:40.830 --> 01:01:42.960
So every time the
generators will

01:01:42.960 --> 01:01:48.100
submit the bids, which says
the following-- I can generate

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:52.570
50 megawatt for a given hour.

01:01:52.570 --> 01:01:55.190
I will generate 50 megawatt.

01:01:55.190 --> 01:01:57.210
If you ask me only
to generate 50,

01:01:57.210 --> 01:02:01.180
I will generate them at $20.

01:02:01.180 --> 01:02:01.680
Why?

01:02:01.680 --> 01:02:05.435
Because I will run my most
efficient power plant,

01:02:05.435 --> 01:02:06.810
which is the
cheapest one to run.

01:02:06.810 --> 01:02:10.260
I will generate 50 megawatts.

01:02:10.260 --> 01:02:12.570
If you want more, if
you want me to-- I'm

01:02:12.570 --> 01:02:15.250
bidding-- if you
want me to do 100,

01:02:15.250 --> 01:02:18.660
then you'll have to
pay me $25, because I

01:02:18.660 --> 01:02:21.450
will have to introduce less
efficient power plants,

01:02:21.450 --> 01:02:22.410
and so on.

01:02:22.410 --> 01:02:25.930
200 to $30, and if you
want me to me generate 600,

01:02:25.930 --> 01:02:29.090
you will have to pay me $50.

01:02:29.090 --> 01:02:32.470
So that's my bid,
so-called bid stack.

01:02:32.470 --> 01:02:35.230
That's what I'm
sending to the auction.

01:02:35.230 --> 01:02:38.220
The other guy is
sending similar things.

01:02:38.220 --> 01:02:41.030
The auctioneer-- there
is an auctioneer,

01:02:41.030 --> 01:02:46.210
organization called independent
system operator, ISO.

01:02:46.210 --> 01:02:48.680
They collect all these bids.

01:02:48.680 --> 01:02:52.050
They know what demand
will be tomorrow.

01:02:52.050 --> 01:02:55.440
They collect, and then
knowing this demand,

01:02:55.440 --> 01:02:58.260
they will-- first of all, they
will sort out all the bids

01:02:58.260 --> 01:03:00.170
in the most optimal way.

01:03:00.170 --> 01:03:06.120
So they'll put it all
together by sorting.

01:03:06.120 --> 01:03:10.555
So this is the auctioneer
combined all these two

01:03:10.555 --> 01:03:14.430
bids, created this
graph-- so basically based

01:03:14.430 --> 01:03:17.970
on how much they
need to generate.

01:03:17.970 --> 01:03:21.524
So based on the demand,
this will be the price.

01:03:21.524 --> 01:03:23.440
That will be the clearing
price of the market.

01:03:23.440 --> 01:03:26.650
And then, because the
auctioneer knows all the bids,

01:03:26.650 --> 01:03:29.367
the auctioneer will
send the demand

01:03:29.367 --> 01:03:30.950
for this generator
and that generator.

01:03:30.950 --> 01:03:35.840
So you will generate 60, you
will generate 600, or whatever.

01:03:35.840 --> 01:03:40.590
The final price is the highest,
basically highest price

01:03:40.590 --> 01:03:43.220
that is necessary
to meet the demand.

01:03:43.220 --> 01:03:46.310
So if the demand is 600,
so this will be the price.

01:03:46.310 --> 01:03:48.600
If it's 800, this
will be the price.

01:03:48.600 --> 01:03:56.500
So the price is
clearly the function

01:03:56.500 --> 01:03:57.840
of demand for any given day.

01:04:01.160 --> 01:04:05.650
Well, even if this
is the case, then

01:04:05.650 --> 01:04:09.050
if I look at the-- if I plot,
do the scatter-plot demand

01:04:09.050 --> 01:04:13.740
versus price, I'll have
to see something similar.

01:04:13.740 --> 01:04:15.080
Well, let's see.

01:04:15.080 --> 01:04:17.670
When we take a
particular market,

01:04:17.670 --> 01:04:22.680
and do the scattered graph,
so demand versus the price,

01:04:22.680 --> 01:04:28.020
you see this is the graph
that we expect to see.

01:04:28.020 --> 01:04:29.390
It's a little bit fat.

01:04:29.390 --> 01:04:31.530
Why is it fat?

01:04:31.530 --> 01:04:32.820
Why is it not a straight line?

01:04:32.820 --> 01:04:36.304
Why is it not the line
as before, but it's fat?

01:04:39.060 --> 01:04:42.740
What is random here?

01:04:42.740 --> 01:04:46.500
Remember I told you
that each generator will

01:04:46.500 --> 01:04:49.900
bid approximately how much
it will cost them to generate

01:04:49.900 --> 01:04:52.850
at the particular day.

01:04:52.850 --> 01:04:55.330
That cost depends
on the fuel price,

01:04:55.330 --> 01:04:56.610
and that is a random number.

01:04:56.610 --> 01:05:00.380
So what you can see here
is a lot of these curves,

01:05:00.380 --> 01:05:04.370
but they are kind of randomly
moving because of the fuel

01:05:04.370 --> 01:05:07.420
price affects the
cost of running.

01:05:07.420 --> 01:05:11.030
But conceptually,
philosophically, this

01:05:11.030 --> 01:05:14.660
is exactly what we discussed--
that these guys will

01:05:14.660 --> 01:05:18.380
bid this curve.

01:05:18.380 --> 01:05:21.730
And depending on the
demand, the price

01:05:21.730 --> 01:05:25.370
will be simply the
value on that curve.

01:05:28.340 --> 01:05:31.320
Are you with me?

01:05:31.320 --> 01:05:33.090
So far so good?

01:05:33.090 --> 01:05:37.500
So this is-- that's what
we're trying to model.

01:05:37.500 --> 01:05:42.040
So if we can model that, if
I can model for every day

01:05:42.040 --> 01:05:46.060
the bid curve that
the auctioneer,

01:05:46.060 --> 01:05:48.350
the independent
system operator, sees,

01:05:48.350 --> 01:05:50.170
I know the price at
that particular day.

01:05:52.820 --> 01:05:56.450
Moreover, I don't want
to get too complicated,

01:05:56.450 --> 01:05:57.950
but in reality,
I don't even have

01:05:57.950 --> 01:05:59.280
to know precisely the curve.

01:05:59.280 --> 01:06:02.590
I kind of have to know
precisely the distribution,

01:06:02.590 --> 01:06:04.650
because remember, for
the value of the option,

01:06:04.650 --> 01:06:07.790
you don't need to know where
the price will be at expiration.

01:06:07.790 --> 01:06:11.970
You just need to know how the
price will be distributed.

01:06:11.970 --> 01:06:14.780
If you catch the
distribution correctly

01:06:14.780 --> 01:06:16.565
through, again,
dynamic hedging and so

01:06:16.565 --> 01:06:18.445
on-- that's what
Black-Scholes tells you--

01:06:18.445 --> 01:06:20.960
you can actually value
the option correctly.

01:06:20.960 --> 01:06:23.330
So you can value the
power plant correctly.

01:06:23.330 --> 01:06:25.240
But that's besides the point.

01:06:25.240 --> 01:06:27.820
The point is right now
I'm trying to model,

01:06:27.820 --> 01:06:33.220
somehow, the randomness
of this bid curve.

01:06:33.220 --> 01:06:41.110
So now, to summarize, the power
price is the function of what?

01:06:41.110 --> 01:06:43.720
Of demand, clearly-- we
already know it is that.

01:06:43.720 --> 01:06:46.560
But also the fuel
prices, because the fuel

01:06:46.560 --> 01:06:49.350
prices determine the
cost of generation

01:06:49.350 --> 01:06:51.950
and therefore, how much
each generator will

01:06:51.950 --> 01:06:54.560
bid into the market.

01:06:54.560 --> 01:06:56.520
That's dependent on the cost.

01:06:56.520 --> 01:06:59.300
If the natural gas
goes through the roof,

01:06:59.300 --> 01:07:02.180
the price of generating one
megawatt will be very high.

01:07:02.180 --> 01:07:03.770
So the person will
be-- the generator

01:07:03.770 --> 01:07:06.520
will be bidding
very high prices.

01:07:06.520 --> 01:07:08.520
And that's what we see here.

01:07:08.520 --> 01:07:10.600
And also outages-- we
have to model outages,

01:07:10.600 --> 01:07:14.220
because the market
is only finite, kind

01:07:14.220 --> 01:07:15.710
of fleet of the power plants.

01:07:15.710 --> 01:07:20.645
And if a couple of them will
go down, the price of power

01:07:20.645 --> 01:07:22.440
can be affected dramatically.

01:07:22.440 --> 01:07:33.330
The 1997, the Indiana-- the
price went from $40 to $7,000

01:07:33.330 --> 01:07:36.960
because tornado hit
the nuclear plant.

01:07:36.960 --> 01:07:41.580
You take a big chunk of the
generation from the stack,

01:07:41.580 --> 01:07:44.740
and all of a sudden,
you have to run

01:07:44.740 --> 01:07:49.190
absolutely anything, including
some very expensive diesels,

01:07:49.190 --> 01:07:49.760
and so on.

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:53.100
So the price of power,
obviously, goes very high.

01:07:55.980 --> 01:08:00.670
OK, so these are three
things that we try to model.

01:08:00.670 --> 01:08:04.070
So how will we model that?

01:08:04.070 --> 01:08:14.340
Well, before even I get
to the modeling of them,

01:08:14.340 --> 01:08:19.040
let me just again outline
our modeling approach.

01:08:19.040 --> 01:08:23.819
If I know the fuel-- let's say
there are no outages-- if I

01:08:23.819 --> 01:08:29.850
know the fuel price,
I know then how much

01:08:29.850 --> 01:08:31.430
each of the
generators-- how much

01:08:31.430 --> 01:08:34.410
it will cost for each of the
generators in the market.

01:08:34.410 --> 01:08:37.069
Because I know
everybody in the market.

01:08:37.069 --> 01:08:42.069
I know how much for each of
them it will cost to generate.

01:08:42.069 --> 01:08:46.020
So fuel, if I know fuel
price, I can generate

01:08:46.020 --> 01:08:47.620
so-called generation stack.

01:08:47.620 --> 01:08:51.810
It means the cost of generation
for each of the generators,

01:08:51.810 --> 01:08:54.340
for each of the
participants in the market.

01:08:54.340 --> 01:08:57.229
The outages will simply
allow me to take out

01:08:57.229 --> 01:09:00.180
some of these participants
out of the picture, basically.

01:09:00.180 --> 01:09:03.830
So I need to know that, but
that's-- at any given day,

01:09:03.830 --> 01:09:06.010
if I know the outages,
I know the fuel prices,

01:09:06.010 --> 01:09:10.569
I can construct the cost of
generating for everybody.

01:09:10.569 --> 01:09:14.529
So it's close to the bid stack.

01:09:14.529 --> 01:09:18.180
It's something that they
will bid-- their cost,

01:09:18.180 --> 01:09:19.260
maybe plus some profit.

01:09:19.260 --> 01:09:21.710
I don't know what their
profit margins are.

01:09:21.710 --> 01:09:25.779
But what I know, I
know the market prices.

01:09:25.779 --> 01:09:28.100
I know the options, how
they trade, and so on.

01:09:28.100 --> 01:09:31.430
So the bid stack
will, in general,

01:09:31.430 --> 01:09:33.120
follow the generation stack.

01:09:33.120 --> 01:09:35.779
It will be, more or less,
the same thing, maybe some

01:09:35.779 --> 01:09:38.000
added profit requirements.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:41.340
But I can back these
profit requirements

01:09:41.340 --> 01:09:43.290
from the market prices.

01:09:43.290 --> 01:09:47.840
That's where my supply-demand
approach and the market

01:09:47.840 --> 01:09:49.630
will get together.

01:09:49.630 --> 01:09:52.750
I will adjust the generation
stack in such a way,

01:09:52.750 --> 01:09:54.920
maybe moving it up and
down in such a way,

01:09:54.920 --> 01:09:57.740
that I matched the
prices, and I matched

01:09:57.740 --> 01:10:02.490
the option prices, so measured
the volatility of the market.

01:10:02.490 --> 01:10:05.830
So now the circle is
completely closed,

01:10:05.830 --> 01:10:09.870
if I can succeed in doing that.

01:10:09.870 --> 01:10:11.060
Questions?

01:10:11.060 --> 01:10:12.390
This is the key.

01:10:17.200 --> 01:10:20.530
Well, let's see
if I can do that.

01:10:20.530 --> 01:10:27.560
So first I want to-- now if
I manage to do that, then

01:10:27.560 --> 01:10:31.725
if I know how to model the
evolution of fuel prices,

01:10:31.725 --> 01:10:35.210
if I know how the
outages are modeled,

01:10:35.210 --> 01:10:39.520
and I model the demand, then
I can determine how the power

01:10:39.520 --> 01:10:43.080
prices will be moving in time.

01:10:43.080 --> 01:10:46.370
So power price is the function
of the bid stack and demand,

01:10:46.370 --> 01:10:47.300
as you remember.

01:10:47.300 --> 01:10:50.510
So if I know the evolution of
the bid stack, the evolution

01:10:50.510 --> 01:10:55.210
of the demand, I can determine
the evolution of the power

01:10:55.210 --> 01:10:56.862
price-- completely
different approach.

01:11:00.114 --> 01:11:02.030
So let's start with the
evolution of the fuel,

01:11:02.030 --> 01:11:04.940
with building the fuel model.

01:11:04.940 --> 01:11:07.250
Well, I told you that
there is natural gas.

01:11:07.250 --> 01:11:10.510
In reality, we have to
model all that stuff.

01:11:10.510 --> 01:11:15.330
Because each of them has a
curve because of volatility.

01:11:15.330 --> 01:11:18.150
It looks a lot,
but in reality it's

01:11:18.150 --> 01:11:21.490
not, because we have
a pretty good idea.

01:11:21.490 --> 01:11:23.810
Unlike the power prices
with the spikes and all

01:11:23.810 --> 01:11:26.330
this crazy behavior, we
have a pretty good idea

01:11:26.330 --> 01:11:29.360
of the behavior of these things,
because they're all storable.

01:11:29.360 --> 01:11:30.940
By the way, power
prices are jumping

01:11:30.940 --> 01:11:33.760
because of non-storability
of power prices,

01:11:33.760 --> 01:11:35.800
because they're not storable.

01:11:35.800 --> 01:11:42.050
Because they're non-storable,
you cannot smooth out

01:11:42.050 --> 01:11:43.960
the changes in the demand.

01:11:43.960 --> 01:11:46.610
Just so you have-- your
action's immediate.

01:11:46.610 --> 01:11:48.440
These are all
storable commodities,

01:11:48.440 --> 01:11:51.020
so the behavior is
much more regular.

01:11:51.020 --> 01:11:54.320
They're much closer, let's
say, to the equity prices.

01:11:54.320 --> 01:11:56.150
And so we can use
some standard models.

01:11:56.150 --> 01:11:59.020
So from the modeling
point of view,

01:11:59.020 --> 01:12:03.320
they are not particularly
difficult to model.

01:12:03.320 --> 01:12:07.550
So particularly just natural
gas, heating oil and fuel oil,

01:12:07.550 --> 01:12:10.440
just the coal-- just we have
a pretty good understanding

01:12:10.440 --> 01:12:12.552
of how these things are modeled.

01:12:18.270 --> 01:12:22.120
Outage, well, we take
the standard model from--

01:12:22.120 --> 01:12:24.950
and reliability
theory provides us

01:12:24.950 --> 01:12:29.520
with a very well-developed
mechanism and apparatus

01:12:29.520 --> 01:12:30.690
how to model these things.

01:12:30.690 --> 01:12:32.940
I mean, usually we do it
through some kind of Poisson,

01:12:32.940 --> 01:12:34.890
or version of Poisson process.

01:12:34.890 --> 01:12:36.891
It is very well understood.

01:12:36.891 --> 01:12:38.390
There's a lot of
literature on that.

01:12:38.390 --> 01:12:40.890
We can model that very easily.

01:12:40.890 --> 01:12:44.520
Where do we have the
parameters for these Poissons?

01:12:44.520 --> 01:12:46.570
The government
provides us with these.

01:12:46.570 --> 01:12:47.700
There's government data.

01:12:47.700 --> 01:12:50.790
Sometimes we get it directly
from the power plants.

01:12:50.790 --> 01:12:55.130
Everybody keeps track of
the frequency of the outages

01:12:55.130 --> 01:12:59.860
and so on and so forth.

01:12:59.860 --> 01:13:02.470
Demand-- how will
we model demand?

01:13:02.470 --> 01:13:07.250
Well, we'll model demand through
the temperature, typically.

01:13:07.250 --> 01:13:07.940
Why temperature?

01:13:07.940 --> 01:13:10.340
Because for temperature,
we have a lot of data.

01:13:10.340 --> 01:13:13.310
It's statistically
a very stable thing.

01:13:13.310 --> 01:13:16.750
So there are many
different approaches

01:13:16.750 --> 01:13:17.750
to modeling temperature.

01:13:22.190 --> 01:13:22.966
It's up to you.

01:13:22.966 --> 01:13:24.590
There's a lot of
literature, so I'm not

01:13:24.590 --> 01:13:26.090
going to go into detail.

01:13:26.090 --> 01:13:28.200
So we choose something.

01:13:28.200 --> 01:13:29.970
We model temperature.

01:13:29.970 --> 01:13:31.460
From that, we model the demand.

01:13:31.460 --> 01:13:33.718
And it works pretty well.

01:13:36.970 --> 01:13:40.480
So now we have-- we modeled
the evolution of temperature,

01:13:40.480 --> 01:13:42.950
evolution of demand,
evolution of fuel,

01:13:42.950 --> 01:13:45.420
evolution of the outages.

01:13:45.420 --> 01:13:50.950
Now we can construct
the generation stack.

01:13:50.950 --> 01:13:57.450
So remember, the generation
was this curve, this curve that

01:13:57.450 --> 01:14:01.820
was a function of demand,
but also the fraction

01:14:01.820 --> 01:14:05.490
of the outages, variable
costs, and so on,

01:14:05.490 --> 01:14:10.800
and the fuel, the vector fuels.

01:14:10.800 --> 01:14:13.240
And then there's
these parameters alpha

01:14:13.240 --> 01:14:15.050
and these alpha
parameters we choose

01:14:15.050 --> 01:14:19.330
to match the futures, the
forward curve for the power

01:14:19.330 --> 01:14:22.730
prices and all other market
parameters as we need.

01:14:22.730 --> 01:14:25.090
So that's how we get-- so
we're matching the market,

01:14:25.090 --> 01:14:34.650
and we're matching the kind of
supply and demand formation.

01:14:34.650 --> 01:14:39.330
Now, it is very clear
why with this approach,

01:14:39.330 --> 01:14:44.540
I can capture spikes without
effort, without any effort.

01:14:44.540 --> 01:14:46.537
And the reason is very simple.

01:14:51.427 --> 01:15:00.260
This is my-- remember the stack,
my bid stack or generation

01:15:00.260 --> 01:15:01.250
stack, whatever.

01:15:01.250 --> 01:15:06.530
So for high generation
volumes, it's

01:15:06.530 --> 01:15:09.190
becoming more and more
expensive to generate.

01:15:09.190 --> 01:15:11.570
And after a certain
time, you've exhausted

01:15:11.570 --> 01:15:13.270
all your cheap plants.

01:15:13.270 --> 01:15:15.410
You have to go to very,
very expensive plants,

01:15:15.410 --> 01:15:17.740
like diesel plants
and so on, which

01:15:17.740 --> 01:15:20.180
runs maybe once in a
lifetime, maybe once a year,

01:15:20.180 --> 01:15:21.050
twice a year.

01:15:21.050 --> 01:15:22.062
And very expensive.

01:15:22.062 --> 01:15:23.270
But they determine the price.

01:15:23.270 --> 01:15:25.960
They are the ones that
determined the clearing price

01:15:25.960 --> 01:15:27.790
at the market.

01:15:27.790 --> 01:15:29.160
Now, let's see.

01:15:29.160 --> 01:15:31.346
If we are somewhere
here-- this is demand.

01:15:31.346 --> 01:15:32.990
Demand is driven by temperature.

01:15:32.990 --> 01:15:37.070
Temperature is
typically a normal thing

01:15:37.070 --> 01:15:38.460
with maybe mean reversion.

01:15:38.460 --> 01:15:42.330
If it goes up, it typically
reverses some mean.

01:15:42.330 --> 01:15:45.400
So this is the distribution
of demand around here.

01:15:45.400 --> 01:15:48.420
Well, if demand
moves left or right,

01:15:48.420 --> 01:15:53.720
up, down, the prices
don't change much.

01:15:53.720 --> 01:15:55.540
So that's your normal regime.

01:15:55.540 --> 01:15:59.840
But let's assume demand
is somewhere here.

01:15:59.840 --> 01:16:03.050
If you are to the left,
the prices are very small.

01:16:03.050 --> 01:16:07.130
But the moment you move a
little bit to the right,

01:16:07.130 --> 01:16:11.240
your temperature moves a
